        text: 'Psychotherapy is still the main treatment for TMS, because the condition comes from the mind rather than from any physical injury. Patients are told to seek therapy instead of trusting in pills or exercise routines they saw on TV.\n\nPeople with TMS often have a long history of rough emotions they have never let out.\n\nThose emotions can be so heavy that even a good therapist has to work hard to loosen them. The job of therapy is to help the patient face the feelings rather than run from them. The patient has to accept that the events that caused the feelings are real, that they belong to the past, and that they cannot hurt anymore. For someone who lost a loved one and carries the weight, therapy can walk them away from the pain, slowly and steadily, in a way that works.\n\nResearch shows that only about five percent of patients need psychotherapy, which is why so few people look for it when they feel stuck.\n\nA few structural conditions get diagnosed by mistake as TMS. It helps to know them, since they are the usual labels for cases that may actually be TMS. Sharp lower back pain gets called a herniated disc, even though by age twenty the part of the spine in question is no longer there to slip. In rare cases, a real structural problem does cause pain, and spinal stenosis is one, but it is uncommon. Even that one gets misdiagnosed as TMS sometimes.\n\nPlenty of structural diagnoses for muscle, nerve, tendon, and ligament pain have no real physical cause. The mind is overlooking TMS and reading what it expects to read. To skip costly and risky procedures, a patient should have a mental check first to see if the pain is real or emotional. Serious treatment should only follow once repressed emotion has been ruled out, so the symptoms do not get worse.'
