        title: 'Forty years later',
        text: 'Each of the six survivors we have followed made their own way in the years after the bomb.\n\nHatsuyo Nakamura recovered her sewing machine and worked every day, fighting through the symptoms of radiation sickness. When her health returned, she took a factory job. Her family received one of the new homes built for Hiroshima survivors, and life finally felt stable. Her children grew up and supported her, and her son eventually bought her a new sewing machine.\n\nDr. Terufumi Sasaki opened his own clinic and built a happy family life with financial security. In 1963, lung cancer showed up, almost certainly tied to the radiation. He beat it, but his wife died of breast cancer not long after. The loss pushed him to save as many lives as he could. He went on to build a nursing home and hot springs, which made him one of the wealthiest men in Hiroshima.\n\nFather Kleinsorge spent the rest of his life dealing with radiation damage. He came to love Japan deeply and adopted the name Father Makoto Takakura. He met the love of his life in Japan and stayed with her until he died.\n\nToshiko Sasaki had multiple surgeries, and her leg pain never went away. She could walk, but her limp convinced her that no one would ever want to marry her. In 1954, Father Takakura encouraged her to visit a convent, and she joined. She took the name Sister Dominique Sasaki, rose to director of the convent, and found peace.\n\nDr. Fujii took up English and felt no bitterness toward his former enemies. In 1956, he traveled to the United States to help the Hiroshima Maidens, young women whose faces had been badly disfigured by the bomb and who were coming over for reconstructive surgery. He played a fatherly role and lifted their spirits. On New Year\'s Eve of 1963, he survived a gas leak, but the damage left him in a vegetative state. He stayed that way until his death in 1973.\n\nKiyoshi Tanimoto was a driving force behind the rebuilding of Hiroshima. During a U.S. visit in 1948, he sketched out the idea of a World Peace Center to stop atomic bombings from ever happening again. The idea drew strong support. He also helped the Hiroshima Maidens once they reached America. After returning home, he kept advocating for disarmament and lived simply.\n\nLook for chances when they come, and put your energy into solutions rather than the negative.'
